<dl id="n54125a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54125a">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54125a"> 125(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> porter of mighty grasp <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54125a"><li>FW 136.04 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n54125a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n54125a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54125a">MS BL 47476a-223</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:469 <a name="fad8" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad8.htm#n54125a">Draft: I.6&sect;1.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The winning of Olwen,&mdash;hard enough though it appears in the story, which is mainly concerned with the long series of laborious tasks imposed upon Kulhwch as conditions of gaining her hand&mdash;is made &ldquo;easy&rdquo; through Arthur&apos;s intervention. The hero starts by duly presenting himself at &ldquo;the gate of Arthur&apos;s palace&rsquo;, and he there meets with <mark>the porter, Glewlwyd of the Mighty Grasp</mark></mark>, who conveys to Arthur the news of his arrival. <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA4" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA4"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 46</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n16049i" href="n16all.htm#n16049i">N16 (VI.D.1):049(i)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
